{
  "result": "On summer evenings the city behaves like a patient animal. Heat rises from pavement, and windows bloom with light. I like to walk without destination, letting the grid pull me along. At the corner bakery, a man waters his tomato plants and the scent of yeast slips into the street. Farther on, a bus exhales, and a boy in headphones sways with each stop.\n\nWalking gives me access to small theaters. A couple argues softly about whether the dog understands them. A grandmother teaches her granddaughter to pronounce the names of stars. A cyclist races his shadow and loses. None of these scenes are meant for me, yet I carry them, like pocket stones, all the way home.\n\nWhen I was younger, I craved places with dramatic histories, but now I am fond of the ordinary. It is ordinary that keeps the world stitched together. People arrive at work, water their plants, kiss the dog, pay the bills. The repetition is not dull; it is a rhythm that holds us. On nights when I cannot sleep, I listen to that rhythm\u2014distant engines, late laughter, a train horn in the harbor.\n\nBy the time I return, my street is quiet. The moon sits on the roofline like a coin. I unlock the door and feel my body arrive. In the morning, the same blocks will pretend nothing happened, but I will remember. The walk will have folded itself into me, adding another layer to the map of my life tonight, forever.",
